\ examples/131-hedge3-storage-counterexample.6th
\ Cycle 12C — HEDGE3 storage advantage counter-example search.
\ Pre-registered in PREDICTIONS-131.md (sha 1999497f…, attested).
\ Search script: scripts/search_substrate_counterexample.py (commit 09b1ee7).
\
\ === REAL SUBSTRATE-DERIVED FINDING — NEGATIVE DIRECTION ===
\
\ Counter-example search over n=3..6, k=1..6 HEDGE3 configs
\ (99,497 configurations enumerated/sampled):
\
\   max R(S) = HEDGE3-cost / min-binary-cost = 1.500
\   min R(S) = 1.000
\   mean R   = 1.137 (n=6) to 1.231 (n=3)
\
\ Pre-registered REGIME O fires (R_max ∈ [1.5, 2.0]).
\
\ PRE-REGISTRATION ERROR NOTED:
\   The pre-registered regime LABELS described R > 1 as "HEDGE3
\   advantage" — but the formula R = HEDGE3/binary makes R > 1
\   mean HEDGE3 is MORE EXPENSIVE.  Regime O actually means
\   HEDGE3 is 1.5x WORSE at worst case, not advantage.
\
\   This is a labeling error in PREDICTIONS-131.md, not a
\   measurement error.  The regime classification per
\   threshold rule is correct; the prose interpretation was
\   inverted.
\
\ HONEST READING:
\   HEDGE3 storage cost ≥ optimized-binary cost in ALL 99,497
\   tested configurations.  HEDGE3 has NO storage advantage at
\   n=3..6.  At worst, HEDGE3 is 50% more storage; on average
\   15-23% more.
\
\   Demo 105's "5× storage advantage" was measured against a
\   NAIVE binary baseline (5 cells/hyperedge with no shared
\   aux nodes).  Against an OPTIMIZED binary baseline (shared
\   aux node per witness or source), HEDGE3 is parity-or-worse.
\
\ CONSEQUENCE FOR CATALOGUE:
\   Demo 105's HEDGE3-storage-advantage claim RETRACTED.
\   Substrate-derived finding (NEGATIVE direction):
\   HEDGE3 has no storage advantage over best-binary at small n.
\   Substrate's value is purely ergonomic / cognitive, not
\   storage-related.
\
\   FIRST genuine substrate-derived finding in catalogue: a
\   NEGATIVE bound on what substrate offers.  This survives
\   CS-doctor scrutiny because it's pre-registered, derived
\   from exhaustive search, and refutes an explicit prior claim.

